		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/paper13</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>Method and Tool Support for Classifying Software Languages with Wikipedia</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>, <a href="../profile/DominikMosen.html">Dominik Mosen</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreiVaranovich.html">Andrei Varanovich</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_14">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_14</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3e.html"><span class="tagM">T3E: Ontologies</span></a><ul><li> The main contribution is a method/tool for building a classification (taxonomy/ontology-like structure) of software languages using Wikipedia categories.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> The tool visualizes the extracted Wikipedia category graph in a navigable, tree-like form to support exploration and understanding.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> It performs analysis/mining over a large knowledge base (Wikipedia) to derive and refine language-classification structures.
</li></ul></li></ul>
